 565: not a point multiplier.
 566: 
 567: **The symmetric credit-versus-coverage gate (methods and result).** Because this
 568: is the paper's one confirmatory computation, its design is stated in full here
 569: rather than only by reference. Each world holds K = 500 candidate projects; for
 570: each, up to N = 5000 potential participants are drawn and each is interested with
 571: a project-specific probability (so reach is endogenous). Both arms then see the
 572: same candidate pool, the same exact costs, the same truth net[j] = S[j] − h·cost[j],
 573: delivery held at **parity**, and the same report noise report = v + Normal(0, τ);
 574: each funds a **greedy** set under a budget of one-third of total project cost, is
 575: eligible to fund a project only where *its own* noisy estimate of net is positive
 576: (no oracle gate), and its delivered value is scored on the projects' *true* net.
 577: The arms are symmetric except for the coverage mechanism and its matched
 578: counterparts. *Distributed (endogenous coverage):* each interested citizen reports
 579: independently with probability p if her value v ≥ 0 and p·(1 − β) if v < 0 (adverse
 580: voice bias), giving ĥS_D = Σreports / p, ranked by estimated net per cost.
 581: *Central (competent value-reader):* an appraisal budget equal to the distributed
 582: arm's *expected* total reports in that world, spread **evenly** across projects
 583: (fixed per-project bandwidth m_C); per project it samples m_C interested citizens,
 584: observes v + Normal(0, τ), and forms its own noisy ĥNet_C = reach·mean(observed) −
 585: h·cost. It ranks by score = (1 − λ)·z(ĥNet_C/cost) + λ·z(P/cost) — its **own noisy
 586: estimate**, never the true net — where P is claimable political credit (the
 587: electoral credit-claiming and traceability logic by which visible, attributable
 588: benefits are favoured over diffuse ones; Mayhew 1974; Arnold 1990) and λ is bounded
 589: credit pressure (a *posited* pressure whose real-world magnitude must be measured,
 590: not assumed). Credit moves *ranking*, never eligibility (no knowingly
 591: value-destroying planner). The legitimate asymmetries are therefore only these:
 592: distributed reports self-route to projects citizens care about while negative
 593: stakeholders participate less, and central appraisal is spread evenly while its
 594: ranking carries credit pressure — everything else is shared. The estimand is
 595: **Δ = (D − C)/O** per world, where D, C, O are delivered true net for the
 596: distributed, central, and full-information greedy arms and O is a reference level,
 597: not an optimum. The frozen grid sweeps λ ∈ {0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3} (λ = 0 a negative
 598: control), a latent-correlation setting ρ ∈ {0, 0.5, 1} (realized corr(S, P) ≈ 0.00,
 599: 0.30, 0.82), and h ∈ {1.5, 2.5, 4} over 100 seeded worlds, in a baseline
 600: observation regime (p = .35, β = .30, τ = .5) and a matched-budget low-information
 601: stress regime (p = .15, β = .60, τ = 1.0). The **pre-registered decision rule** —
 602: frozen before running and designed by the independent auditor to be adversarial —
 603: required, for a GO on rebuilding the quantitative engine, at least 15 of the 18
 604: primary cells with mean Δ > 0, a pooled **median Δ ≥ 0.05**, a bootstrap lower
 605: bound > 0, and median Δ ≥ 0 under the stress regime, plus a guard to pause if the
 606: λ = 0 control itself exceeded 0.05. The result was **NO-GO**: the advantage was
 607: positive in all 18 primary cells, but the pre-registered pooled **median Δ = 0.025**,
 608: below the 0.05 rebuild gate; the λ = 0 negative control sat at ≈ 0.016, within the
 609: pause guard (no hidden asymmetry flagged). A **post-hoc** world-cluster
 610: ratio-of-sums estimate was Δ = 0.026 [0.023, 0.029] (Monte-Carlo uncertainty on the
 611: simulated data-generating process, reported separately from the median). The
 612: advantage rises with credit pressure λ and falls as credit aligns with value — the
 613: credit-versus-coverage mechanism — but it is small, which is why the calibrated
 614: multiplier is retired and the paper rests on the architecture and the mechanism
 615: direction.
 616: 
 617: **Finding 1: funding caps are an anti-concentration device, not a quality
 618: device.** With closure ON, concentration falls (funding Gini 0.732 vs
 619: 0.759), the most salient 5% of projects absorb less (16.8% vs 19.6% of all
 620: funding), and 15% more projects complete (25.3% vs 21.9%). But quality
 621: selection is unchanged (*sel(θ)*, the Pearson correlation across projects between
 622: latent quality θ and the binary indicator that a project reaches its funding
 623: target, ≈ 0.39 vs 0.41): the truncated surplus
 624: spills to the next most *visible* project, not the next *best* one. The
 625: architecture's claim for the closure rule should be — and in the corpus now
1245: arrived sponsors, in the places that need it least.
1246: 
1247: **The outcome measure is a bounded, non-distributional aggregate.** The value
1248: the model scores is a cardinal utilitarian-style sum over affected parties on a
1249: bounded, infrastructure-like public-investment slice; it is not distributionally
1250: weighted and says nothing about redistribution, equity, or who bears benefits and
1251: harms. A portfolio can score well on this measure while distributing badly.
1252: Applying the criterion across groups, or to the whole budget or the purpose of
1253: taxation, would require a separate social-welfare and incidence specification this
1254: paper does not provide. The model is also partial-equilibrium: strategic
1255: reporting, endogenous proposal supply, project complementarities, tax incidence,
1256: and general-equilibrium effects are outside it (see the
1257: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md)).
1258: 
1259: **Epistemically, this is one team's self-critiqued design.** The
1260: adversarial corpus was produced by the same research effort it attacks,
1261: with AI assistance; the earlier apparatus's status-quo baseline was
1262: audit-parameterized (its parameters drawn item-by-item from published
1370: selection gain that interact rather than merely add — but those
1371: magnitudes are model-internal factorial contrasts, not calibrated
1372: effects, and we do not build the paper on them. The claim the paper
1373: actually stands on is narrower and was tested harder: a pre-registered,
1374: symmetric, selection-only gate finds the distributed-minus-central
1375: advantage positive in every cell but small (a pre-registered pooled median
1376: Δ = 0.025 of a full-information benchmark, below its pre-set 0.05
1377: research-program rebuild gate), so we retire the compound multiplier an
1378: earlier version reported and rest on the architecture and the *direction*
1379: of the mechanism. One model-internal result is worth carrying because it is
1380: about the delivery layer, not the multiplier: in the model, at E7's
1381: audit-informed (but not yet fully source-verified) detection intensity,
1382: detection without persistent consequences deters no diversion; what moves delivered value is the
1383: instrument the modelled status quo lacks — consequences that persist. Whether
1384: that holds in a real institution is a hypothesis for a pilot, not a result
1385: here; but the model is unambiguous that accountability without memory is
1386: bookkeeping.
1387: 
1388: The deeper point is Friedman's: a central administration spends other
1389: people's money on other people, the spending category with the least care
1390: for both cost and value (Friedman and Friedman 1980). This architecture
